The Attorney General of Indonesia ('''''Jaksa Agung Republik Indonesia''''') is the competent authority to advise the [[Government of Indonesia]] on matters of law.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indonesia.go.id/en/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=297&Itemid=1767 |title=indonesia.go.id |access-date=2016-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120924061928/http://www.indonesia.go.id/en/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=297&Itemid=1767 |archive-date=2012-09-24 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> The Attorney General represents the government at the [[Supreme Court of Indonesia]] and is a [[Cabinet of Indonesia|Cabinet-level]] official. The office is not part of the Justice Department, however, as the cabinet has its own [[Ministry of Law and Human Rights (Indonesia)|Law and Human Rights department]] (''Kementerian Hukum dan Hak Asasi Manusia'') with a separate [[List of Ministers of Law and Human Rights (Indonesia)|Minister of Law and Human Rights]] (''Menteri Hukum dan Hak Asasi Manusia'') that focuses on more technical matters and regulation making rather than executing the Supreme Court's order. 

The Attorney General is also a Solicitor General. Thus, the Attorney General can represent the Government in the Supreme Court. The Attorney General has the power to indict and prosecute outlaws and law breakers. The term of office of the Attorney General was determined by the [[Constitutional Court of Indonesia]] in 2010 to be concurrent with the term of office of the [[President of Indonesia]].<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/foreign-news/article/indonesia-attorney-general-told-to-step-down-following-ruling-of-constitutional-court/ Global Legal Monitor]</ref> The current Attorney General of Indonesia of Indonesia is [[Muhammad Prasetyo|HM Prasetyo]], who assumed office in 2014.

